Inception

Description

“You’re waiting for a train. A train that will take you far away.”

This is a white-box challenge. The source code of the Flask application is provided.

Initial Analysis

The application includes an internal endpoint:

@app.route('/internal/flag')
def get_internal_flag():
    if request.remote_addr != '127.0.0.1':
        return "Forbidden", 403
    return "flag{Dummy_flag_dont_submit}", 200

The flag is only accessible from localhost (127.0.0.1).

The /check endpoint allows users to submit a URL, which the server fetches using a custom redirect handler.

Vulnerable Logic

The key vulnerability lies in how redirects are handled.

custom_fetch() behavior:

Redirects are handled manually

allow_redirects=False

Maximum redirects: 10

If exceeded, a TooManyRedirectsError is raised

Error handling flaw:

When an exception occurs, the application does the following:

last_url = str(e).split("Last URL was: ")[1]
final_attempt = requests.get(last_url, timeout=2)

This second requests.get():

Uses default behavior

Allows redirects

Fetches the last_url without restrictions

This creates an SSRF via redirect chaining.

Exploitation Strategy

Trigger a redirect loop exceeding 10 redirects

Control the final URL included in the exception message

Force the second request to follow redirects to:

http://127.0.0.1:8000/internal/flag
Exploit Implementation

A PHP script was written and hosted externally. The script:

Redirects to itself 10 times

On the final redirect, points to /internal/flag

When submitted to /check, the backend:

Hits redirect limit

Extracts the final URL

Performs a new unrestricted request

Fetches the internal flag endpoint

Result

The server fetches the internal endpoint on behalf of the attacker and returns the flag.
